Income & Currency Engine Flow

  This feature starts when the user opens app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/ui/screens/
  income/AddIncomeScreen.kt:1 from the Home quick action and ends with a normalized
  income record being stored locally, synced to Firestore, and later used by the
  dashboard through baseAmountLKR.

  ## 1. UI Layer

  What the user sees

  - The Add Income screen has:
      - amount input
      - currency selector: LKR, USD, USDT
      - income type selector: Salary, Freelance, Crypto
      - conversion preview card
      - Save Income button

  What interactions happen

  - As soon as the user enters a valid amount and picks a currency, the screen
    automatically asks for conversion data.
  - This is triggered from the screen itself through onFetchExchangeRate(...), which
    forwards the request to IncomeViewModel.

  How conversion preview works

  - If the currency is LKR, the preview is immediate: entered amount = LKR amount.
  - If the currency is foreign, the card shows:
      - a loading state: “Fetching live exchange rate...”
      - then a preview like 50 USD ≈ 15000 LKR
      - and the rate line like 1 USD = ... LKR
  - If conversion fails, the preview card shows the error.
  - The save button stays disabled while:
      - the amount is invalid
      - conversion is still loading
      - conversion failed and no LKR value is resolved

  Main file: app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/ui/screens/income/AddIncomeScreen.kt:1

  ## 2. ViewModel Layer

  What IncomeViewModel handles

  - IncomeViewModel is the controller for this whole feature.
  - It manages:
      - exchange-rate loading
      - converted LKR amount
      - validation errors
      - save loading/success/error state

  How state updates work

  - The screen observes a single StateFlow of app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/ui/
    screens/income/IncomeUiState.kt:1.
  - That state contains:
      - exchangeRate
      - convertedAmountLKR
      - isExchangeRateLoading
      - isLoading
      - isSuccess
      - error messages

  How conversion/save flow is controlled

  - fetchExchangeRate(amount, currency)
      - validates the amount
      - handles direct LKR case locally
      - otherwise asks the repository for the live rate
      - stores both the rate and converted LKR value in UI state
  - saveIncome(amount, currency, category)
      - validates amount
      - resolves the final exchange rate and final baseAmountLKR
      - blocks saving if foreign-currency conversion is unavailable
      - gets the logged-in Firebase user ID
      - builds a Transaction
      - sends it to FinanceRepository.saveIncome(...)

  Main file: app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/ui/screens/income/IncomeViewModel.kt:1

  ## 3. Currency Conversion Flow

  How exchange rates are fetched

  - IncomeViewModel calls FinanceRepository.getExchangeRate(currency).
  - FinanceRepository uses Retrofit through:
      - app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/data/remote/RetrofitClient.kt:1
      - app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/data/remote/ExchangeRateApi.kt:1
  - The API endpoint returns a full exchange-rate response.

  How conversion is calculated

  - The repository fetches the selected base currency’s latest rates.
  - It specifically extracts the LKR rate from the response.
  - Then IncomeViewModel calculates:

  convertedAmountLKR = amount * exchangeRate

  How LKR values are generated

  - For LKR input:
      - exchangeRate = 1.0
      - baseAmountLKR = amount
  - For foreign currency:
      - the fetched LKR rate is used
      - the converted LKR result becomes the normalized amount stored for later totals

  Important model: app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/data/model/ExchangeRateResponse.kt:1

  ## 4. Repository Flow

  How FinanceRepository handles saving

  - saveIncome(...) is a thin entry point.
  - It forwards to the main save pipeline: saveTransaction(...).

  Room-first behavior

  - saveTransaction(...) always writes to Room first.
  - That means the transaction is inserted into the local transactions table immediately.
  - This is done through app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/data/local/
    TransactionDao.kt:1.

  Firestore sync behavior

  - After the Room insert, the repository starts a background Firestore upload.
  - It sends the transaction to the transactions collection in Firestore using the same
    transaction ID.
  - If upload succeeds:
      - Room marks that row as isSynced = true
  - If upload fails:
      - the row remains in Room with isSynced = false

  Main file: app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/data/repository/FinanceRepository.kt:1

  ## 5. Offline Behavior

  What happens without internet

  - Saving still works because Room is written first.
  - So the user can still add income offline.
  - The app can show save success even before Firestore has finished syncing.

  How retry/sync works later

  - Unsynced transactions remain stored locally with isSynced = false.
  - app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/data/worker/SyncWorker.kt:1 periodically retries
    those records.
  - app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/PbdApplication.kt:1 schedules that worker every 15
    minutes with a network-required constraint.
  - When internet is available, the worker calls
    FinanceRepository.syncUnsyncedTransactions() and pushes pending items to Firestore.

  Important practical note:

  - This feature is offline-safe for saving.
  - But the dashboard reads from Firestore, not Room, so a newly saved offline income
    will not appear on the dashboard until sync succeeds.

  ## 6. Dashboard/Data Usage

  How saved converted values are later used

  - The key field is baseAmountLKR.
  - That is the normalized value used for totals, regardless of whether the original
    income was in LKR, USD, or USDT.

  How dashboard totals are calculated

  - app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/data/repository/DashboardRepository.kt:1 reads
    transactions from Firestore for the current user.
  - app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/ui/screens/dashboard/DashboardViewModel.kt:1 then:
      - sums baseAmountLKR for INCOME
      - sums baseAmountLKR for EXPENSE
      - calculates netBalance = income - expenses
      - shows recent transactions

  So the feature’s main design idea is:

  - original amount and original currency are preserved
  - normalized baseAmountLKR is used for analytics and balance calculations

  ## 7. Important Models

  Transaction

  - Main financial record model.
  - Stores:
      - original amount
      - original currency
      - exchange rate used
      - converted baseAmountLKR
      - type (INCOME or EXPENSE)
      - category
      - timestamp
      - sync status
  - File: app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/data/model/Transaction.kt:1

  IncomeUiState

  - UI state holder for the Add Income feature.
  - Keeps both conversion state and save state in one place.
  - File: app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/ui/screens/income/IncomeUiState.kt:1

  ExchangeRateResponse

  - Represents the API response from the exchange-rate service.
  - Holds:
      - request result
      - base currency code
      - dynamic rates map
  - File: app/src/main/java/com/example/pbd/data/model/ExchangeRateResponse.kt:1

  ## 8. Overall Architecture Flow

  Home Screen Quick Action
  ↓
  AddIncomeScreen (Compose UI)
  ↓
  IncomeViewModel
  ↓
  FinanceRepository
  ↓
  Room (save immediately)
  ↓
  Background Firestore upload
  ↓
  SyncWorker retries later if needed
  ↓
  DashboardRepository reads from Firestore
  ↓
  DashboardViewModel calculates totals using baseAmountLKR

  ## Complete Feature Flow in Practical Steps

  User opens Add Income screen
  ↓
  Enters amount
  ↓
  Selects currency and income type
  ↓
  UI triggers live conversion request
  ↓
  IncomeViewModel resolves exchange rate
  ↓
  LKR preview is shown
  ↓
  User taps Save Income
  ↓
  IncomeViewModel builds Transaction with:
  - amount
  - currency
  - exchangeRate
  - baseAmountLKR
  - type = INCOME
  ↓
  FinanceRepository saves to Room first
  ↓
  Repository tries Firestore sync in background
  ↓
  If sync succeeds, local record is marked synced
  ↓
  If sync fails, record stays unsynced
  ↓
  SyncWorker retries later when internet is available
  ↓
  Firestore transactions are read by DashboardRepository
  ↓
  DashboardViewModel uses baseAmountLKR for income totals and balance

  ## Short Summary

  What makes this feature technically strong

  - Clear UI -> ViewModel -> Repository flow
  - Live conversion before save
  - Normalized baseAmountLKR design, which makes totals simple and consistent
  - Room-first saving gives offline-safe transaction capture
  - Firestore sync is separated, so network delay does not block the form

  Pending / future improvements

  - Dashboard currently depends on Firestore only, so offline-saved incomes are not
    instantly reflected there
  - No local caching of exchange rates yet
  - Firestore sync success is not directly exposed to the user as a separate status
  - The sync path is simple periodic retry; it could be improved with stronger retry/
    backoff reporting